triggers.name: General Recommendation
triggers.recommendation:
This species was recently designated by USFWS as a candidate species across the entire U.S. Candidate species are not statutorily protected under the Endangered Species Act, and therefore effects to the butterfly from this project are not unlawful (although consideration of this species may be required if the project is on federal lands or subject to NEPA environmental review). However, effects to the butterfly could become unlawful in the future should the USFWS decide to list it as endangered or threatened, a process which could take up to 4 years or more.

Transect is working to update this species profile with state-specific range information.

triggers.name: California EO
triggers.recommendation: A nest site (past or present) has been recorded in the vicinity. Field confirmation is recommended to confirm nest presence. If present, USFWS recommends avoiding activities within 1 mile of the nest, but this distance may increase or decrease depending on specific site or activity circumstances.

triggers.name: Solar + California
triggers.recommendation: Potential risk from the solar industry is mostly unknown, but is likely indirect, occurring through loss of foraging habitat.

triggers.name: New York
triggers.recommendation: Consideration of this bird is only required if eagles are nesting or roosting on or within 0.5 mile of the site. Golden eagles are no longer known to nest in New York, but they are known to winter in the state with a few summer occurrences. Consideration is not warranted for eagles that are solely flying overhead.

triggers.name: range_usfws
triggers.recommendation: Stopover habitat may be located on-site or in the vicinity of the project. A habitat assessment is not recommended.
